# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alginic-acid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alginic-acid/aceglutamide-aluminum] Aceglutamide is used as a psychostimulant and nootropic, while aceglutamide aluminium is used in the treatment of ulcers.
[src:alginic-acid/aceglutamide-aluminum] Aceglutamide can also be used as a liquid-stable source of glutamine to prevent damage from protein energy malnutrition.
[src:alginic-acid/aceglutamide-aluminum] The drug has shown neuroprotective effects in an animal model of cerebral ischemia.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, an **acid dissociation constant** (also known as **acidity constant**, or **acid-ionization constant**; denoted ⁠ $K_{a}$ ⁠) is a quantitative measure of the strength of an acid in solution.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] known as dissociation in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The chemical species HA is an acid that dissociates into A−, called the conjugate base of the acid, and a hydrogen ion, H+.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The system is said to be in equilibrium when the concentrations of its components do not change over time, because both forward and backward reactions are occurring at the same rate.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where quantities in square brackets represent the molar concentrations of the species at equilibrium.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, a hypothetical weak acid having *K*a = 10−5, the value of log *K*a is the exponent (−5), giving p*K*a = 5.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A lower *K*a corresponds to a weaker acid (an acid that is less dissociated at equilibrium).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The form p*K*a is often used because it provides a convenient logarithmic scale, and a lower p*K*a corresponds to a stronger acid.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid dissociation constant for an acid is a direct consequence of the underlying thermodynamics of the dissociation reaction; the p*K*a value is directly proportional to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of the p*K*a changes with temperature and can be understood qualitatively based on Le Chatelier's principle: when the reaction is endothermic, *K*a increases and p*K*a decreases with increasing temperature; the opposite is true for exothermic reactions.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of p*K*a also depends on molecular structure of the acid in many ways.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, Linus Pauling proposed two rules: one for successive p*K*a of polyprotic acids (see Polyprotic acids below), and one to estimate the p*K*a of oxyacids based on the number of =O and −OH groups (see Factors that affect p*K*a values below).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other structural factors that influence the magnitude of the acid dissociation constant include inductive effects, mesomeric effects, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hammett type equations have frequently been applied to the estimation of p*K*a.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantitative behaviour of acids and bases in solution can be understood only if their p*K*a values are known.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In particular, the pH of a solution can be predicted when the analytical concentration and p*K*a values of all acids and bases are known; conversely, it is possible to calculate the equilibrium concentration of the acids and bases in solution when the pH is known.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These calculations find application in many different areas of chemistry, biology, medicine, and geology.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, many compounds used for medication are weak acids or bases, and a knowledge of the p*K*a values, together with the octanol-water partition coefficient, can be used for estimating the extent to which the compound enters the blood stream.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acid dissociation constants are also essential in aquatic chemistry and chemical oceanography, where the acidity of water plays a fundamental role.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In living organisms, acid–base homeostasis and enzyme kinetics are dependent on the p*K*a values of the many acids and bases present in the cell and in the body.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, a knowledge of p*K*a values is necessary for the preparation of buffer solutions and is also a prerequisite for a quantitative understanding of the interaction between acids or bases and metal ions to form complexes.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Experimentally, p*K*a values can be determined by potentiometric (pH) titration, but for values of p*K*a less than about 2 or more than about 11, spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be required due to practical difficulties with pH measurements.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constant for this dissociation reaction is known as a dissociation constant.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid loses a proton, leaving a conjugate base; the proton is transferred to the base, creating a conjugate acid.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions of an acid HA, the base is water; the conjugate base is A− and the conjugate acid is the hydronium ion.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Brønsted–Lowry definition applies to other solvents, such as dimethyl sulfoxide: the solvent S acts as a base, accepting a proton and forming the conjugate acid SH+.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In solution chemistry, it is common to use H+ as an abbreviation for the solvated hydrogen ion, regardless of the solvent.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated hydronium ion rather than a proton.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The designation of an acid or base as "conjugate" depends on the context.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The hydroxide ion OH−, a well known base, is here acting as the conjugate base of the acid water.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acids and bases are thus regarded simply as donors and acceptors of protons respectively.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A broader definition of acid dissociation includes hydrolysis, in which protons are produced by the splitting of water molecules.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Lewis's original definition, an acid is a substance that accepts an electron pair to form a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid dissociation constant is a particular example of an equilibrium constant.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $\{X\}$ represents the activity, at equilibrium, of the chemical species X. $K^{\ominus }$ is dimensionless since activity is dimensionless.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Activities of the products of dissociation are placed in the numerator, activities of the reactants are placed in the denominator.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] See activity coefficient for a derivation of this expression.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $[{\text{HA}}]$ represents the concentration of HA and ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ is a quotient of activity coefficients.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To avoid the complications involved in using activities, dissociation constants are determined, where possible, in a medium of high ionic strength, that is, under conditions in which ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ can be assumed to be always constant.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the medium might be a solution of 0.1 molar (M) sodium nitrate or 3 M potassium perchlorate.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note, however, that all published dissociation constant values refer to the specific ionic medium used in their determination and that different values are obtained with different conditions, as shown for acetic acid in the illustration above.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that in the context of metal-ligand complex formation, the equilibrium constants for the formation of metal complexes are usually defined as *association* constants.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In that case, the equilibrium constants for ligand protonation are also defined as association constants.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When discussing the properties of acids it is usual to specify equilibrium constants as acid dissociation constants, denoted by *K*a, with numerical values given the symbol p*K*a.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the other hand, association constants are used for bases.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, general purpose computer programs that are used to derive equilibrium constant values from experimental data use association constants for both acids and bases.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because stability constants for a metal-ligand complex are always specified as association constants, ligand protonation must also be specified as an association reaction.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The association constant for the formation of a supramolecular complex may be denoted as Ka; in such cases "a" stands for "association", not "acid".
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For polyprotic acids, the numbering of stepwise association constants is the reverse of the numbering of the dissociation constants.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] ⁠ R ⁠ is the gas constant and ⁠ T ⁠ is the absolute temperature.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus, for exothermic reactions, the standard enthalpy change, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠, is negative and *K* decreases with temperature.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For endothermic reactions, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is positive and *K* increases with temperature.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where ⁠ $\Delta C_{p}$ ⁠ is the heat capacity change at constant pressure.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ may be taken to be constant over a small temperature range.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express each concentration value as the ratio c/c0, where c0 is the concentration in a [hypothetical] standard state, with a numerical value of 1, by definition.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express the concentrations on the mole fraction scale.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since mole fraction has no dimension, the quotient of concentrations will, by definition, be a pure number.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first and second options above give identical numerical values for an equilibrium constant.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is common practice in biochemistry to quote a value with a dimension as, for example, "*K*a = 30 mM" in order to indicate the scale, millimolar (mM) or micromolar (μM) of the concentration values used for its calculation.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid is classified as "strong" when the concentration of its undissociated species is too low to be measured.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Any aqueous acid with a p*K*a value of less than 0 is almost completely deprotonated and is considered a *strong acid*.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] All such acids transfer their protons to water and form the solvent cation species (H3O+ in aqueous solution) so that they all have essentially the same acidity, a phenomenon known as solvent leveling.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They are said to be *fully dissociated* in aqueous solution because the amount of undissociated acid, in equilibrium with the dissociation products, is below the detection limit.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Likewise, any aqueous base with an association constant p*K*b less than about 0, corresponding to p*K*a greater than about 14, is leveled to OH− and is considered a *strong base*.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nitric acid, with a p*K* value of around −1.7, behaves as a strong acid in aqueous solutions with a pH greater than 1.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At lower pH values it behaves as a weak acid.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values for strong acids have been estimated by theoretical means.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the p*K*a value of aqueous HCl has been estimated as −9.3.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation, from which the following conclusions can be drawn.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In water, measurable p*K*a values range from about −2 for a strong acid to about 12 for a very weak acid (or strong base).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A buffer solution of a desired pH can be prepared as a mixture of a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice, the mixture can be created by dissolving the acid in water, and adding the requisite amount of strong acid or base.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the p*K*a and analytical concentration of the acid are known, the extent of dissociation and pH of a solution of a monoprotic acid can be easily calculated using an ICE table.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A polyprotic acid is a compound which may lose more than 1 proton.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Stepwise dissociation constants are each defined for the loss of a single proton.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1 and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Phosphoric acid, H3PO4, is an example of a polyprotic acid as it can lose three protons.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The species distribution diagram shows that the concentrations of the two ions are maximum at pH 5.5 and 10.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the difference between successive p*K* values is less than about four there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The smaller the difference, the more the overlap.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The case of citric acid is shown at the right; solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Pauling's first rule, successive p*K* values of a given acid increase (p*K*a2 > p*K*a1).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For oxyacids with more than one ionizable hydrogen on the same atom, the p*K*a values often increase by about 5 units for each proton removed, as in the example of phosphoric acid above.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It can be seen in the table above that the second proton is removed from a negatively charged species.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since the proton carries a positive charge extra work is needed to remove it, which is why p*K*a2 is greater than p*K*a1. p*K*a3 is greater than p*K*a2 because there is further charge separation.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When an exception to Pauling's rule is found, it indicates that a major change in structure is also occurring.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case of VO+2(aq), the vanadium is octahedral, 6-coordinate, whereas vanadic acid is tetrahedral, 4-coordinate.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This means that four "particles" are released with the first dissociation, but only two "particles" are released with the other dissociations, resulting in a much greater entropy contribution to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the first reaction than for the others.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For substances in solution, the isoelectric point (p*I*) is defined as the pH at which the sum, weighted by charge value, of concentrations of positively charged species is equal to the weighted sum of concentrations of negatively charged species.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case that there is one species of each type, the isoelectric point can be obtained directly from the p*K* values.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Take the example of glycine, defined as AH.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] There are two dissociation equilibria to consider.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*I* values for amino acids are listed at proteinogenic amino acid.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When more than two charged species are in equilibrium with each other a full speciation calculation may be needed.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When *K*a, *K*b and *K*w are determined under the same conditions of temperature and ionic strength, it follows, taking cologarithms, that p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] with sufficient accuracy for most practical purposes.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In effect there is no need to define p*K*b separately from p*K*a, but it is done here as often only p*K*b values can be found in the older literature.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the reciprocal of an association constant for formation of the complex.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because the relationship p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a holds only in aqueous solutions (though analogous relationships apply for other amphoteric solvents), subdisciplines of chemistry like organic chemistry that usually deal with nonaqueous solutions generally do not use p*K*b as a measure of basicity.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Instead, the p*K*a of the conjugate acid, denoted by p*K*aH, is quoted when basicity needs to be quantified.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A higher value for p*K*aH corresponds to a stronger base.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the values p*K*aH (C5H5N) = 5.25 and p*K*aH ((CH3CH2)3N) = 10.75 indicate that (CH3CH2)3N (triethylamine) is a stronger base than C5H5N (pyridine).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amphoteric substance is one that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Carbonic acid equilibria are important for acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amino acid is also amphoteric with the added complication that the neutral molecule is subject to an internal acid–base equilibrium in which the basic amino group attracts and binds the proton from the acidic carboxyl group, forming a zwitterion.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At pH less than about 5 both the carboxylate group and the amino group are protonated.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At high pH a second dissociation may take place.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus the amino acid molecule is amphoteric because it may either be protonated or deprotonated.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The water molecule may either gain or lose a proton.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where in aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated proton.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Often this is written as the hydronium ion H3O+, but this formula is not exact because in fact there is solvation by more than one water molecule and species such as H5O+2, H7O+3, and H9O+4 are also present.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The self-ionization constant of water, *K*w, is thus just a special case of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At that temperature both hydrogen and hydroxide ions have a concentration of 10−7 M.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high donor number, making it a strong Lewis base.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high dielectric constant (relative permittivity), making it a good solvent for ionic species.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values of organic compounds are often obtained using the aprotic solvents dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and acetonitrile (ACN).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] DMSO is widely used as an alternative to water because it has a lower dielectric constant than water, and is less polar and so dissolves non-polar, hydrophobic substances more easily.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a measurable p*K*a range of about 1 to 30.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acetonitrile is less basic than DMSO, and, so, in general, acids are weaker and bases are stronger in this solvent.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Some p*K*a values at 25 °C for acetonitrile (ACN) and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). are shown in the following tables.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Values for water are included for comparison.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ionization of acids is less in an acidic solvent than in water.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, hydrogen chloride is a weak acid when dissolved in acetic acid.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is because acetic acid is a much weaker base than water.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The unlikely geminal diol species CH3C(OH)+2 is stable in these environments.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions the pH scale is the most convenient acidity function.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other acidity functions have been proposed for non-aqueous media, the most notable being the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aprotic solvents, oligomers, such as the well-known acetic acid dimer, may be formed by hydrogen bonding.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid may also form hydrogen bonds to its conjugate base.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This process, known as homoconjugation, has the effect of enhancing the acidity of acids, lowering their effective p*K*a values, by stabilizing the conjugate base.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Homoconjugation enhances the proton-donating power of toluenesulfonic acid in acetonitrile solution by a factor of nearly 800.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solutions, homoconjugation does not occur, because water forms stronger hydrogen bonds to the conjugate base than does the acid.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a compound has limited solubility in water it is common practice (in the pharmaceutical industry, for example) to determine p*K*a values in a solvent mixture such as water/dioxane or water/methanol, in which the compound is more soluble.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the example shown at the right, the p*K*a value rises steeply with increasing percentage of dioxane as the dielectric constant of the mixture is decreasing.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A p*K*a value obtained in a mixed solvent cannot be used directly for aqueous solutions.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this is that when the solvent is in its standard state its activity is *defined* as one.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the standard state of water:dioxane mixture with 9:1 mixing ratio is precisely that solvent mixture, with no added solutes.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To obtain the p*K*a value for use with aqueous solutions it has to be extrapolated to zero co-solvent concentration from values obtained from various co-solvent mixtures.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These facts are obscured by the omission of the solvent from the expression that is normally used to define p*K*a, but p*K*a values obtained in a *given* mixed solvent can be compared to each other, giving relative acid strengths.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The same is true of p*K*a values obtained in a particular non-aqueous solvent such a DMSO.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A universal, solvent-independent, scale for acid dissociation constants has not been developed, since there is no known way to compare the standard states of two different solvents.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Pauling's second rule is that the value of the first p*K*a for acids of the formula XO*m*(OH)*n* depends primarily on the number of oxo groups *m*, and is approximately independent of the number of hydroxy groups *n*, and also of the central atom X.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alternatively, various numerical formulas have been proposed including p*K*a = 8 − 5*m* (known as Bell's rule), p*K*a = 7 − 5*m*, or p*K*a = 9 − 7*m*.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The dependence on *m* correlates with the oxidation state of the central atom, X: the higher the oxidation state the stronger the oxyacid.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, p*K*a for HClO is 7.2, for HClO2 is 2.0, for HClO3 is −1 and HClO4 is a strong acid (p*K*a ≪ 0).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The increased acidity on adding an oxo group is due to stabilization of the conjugate base by delocalization of its negative charge over an additional oxygen atom.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This rule can help assign molecular structure: for example, phosphorous acid, having molecular formula H3PO3, has a p*K*a near 2, which suggested that the structure is HPO(OH)2, as later confirmed by NMR spectroscopy, and not P(OH)3, which would be expected to have a p*K*a near 8.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Inductive effects and mesomeric effects affect the p*K*a values.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A simple example is provided by the effect of replacing the hydrogen atoms in acetic acid by the more electronegative chlorine atom.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The electron-withdrawing effect of the substituent makes ionisation easier, so successive p*K*a values decrease in the series 4.7, 2.8, 1.4, and 0.7 when 0, 1, 2, or 3 chlorine atoms are present.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Hammett equation, provides a general expression for the effect of substituents.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alcohols do not normally behave as acids in water, but the presence of a double bond adjacent to the OH group can substantially decrease the p*K*a by the mechanism of keto–enol tautomerism.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ascorbic acid is an example of this effect.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The diketone 2,4-pentanedione (acetylacetone) is also a weak acid because of the keto–enol equilibrium.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aromatic compounds, such as phenol, which have an OH substituent, conjugation with the aromatic ring as a whole greatly increases the stability of the deprotonated form.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Structural effects can also be important.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The difference between fumaric acid and maleic acid is a classic example.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid is (E)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid, a *trans* isomer, whereas maleic acid is the corresponding *cis* isomer, i.e.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (Z)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid (see cis-trans isomerism).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid has p*K*a values of approximately 3.0 and 4.5.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] By contrast, maleic acid has p*K*a values of approximately 1.5 and 6.5.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this large difference is that when one proton is removed from the *cis* isomer (maleic acid) a strong intramolecular hydrogen bond is formed with the nearby remaining carboxyl group.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This favors the formation of the maleate H+, and it opposes the removal of the second proton from that species.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the *trans* isomer, the two carboxyl groups are always far apart, so hydrogen bonding is not observed.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Proton sponge, 1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene, has a p*K*a value of 12.1.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is one of the strongest amine bases known.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The high basicity is attributed to the relief of strain upon protonation and strong internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Effects of the solvent and solvation should be mentioned also in this section.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It turns out, these influences are more subtle than that of a dielectric medium mentioned above.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the expected (by electronic effects of methyl substituents) and observed in gas phase order of basicity of methylamines, Me3N > Me2NH > MeNH2 > NH3, is changed by water to Me2NH > MeNH2 > Me3N > NH3.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Neutral methylamine molecules are hydrogen-bonded to water molecules mainly through one acceptor, N–HOH, interaction and only occasionally just one more donor bond, NH–OH2.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hence, methylamines are stabilized to about the same extent by hydration, regardless of the number of methyl groups.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In stark contrast, corresponding methylammonium cations always utilize **all** the available protons for donor NH–OH2 bonding.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Relative stabilization of methylammonium ions thus decreases with the number of methyl groups explaining the order of water basicity of methylamines.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The standard enthalpy change can be determined by calorimetry or by using the van 't Hoff equation, though the calorimetric method is preferable.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When both the standard enthalpy change and acid dissociation constant have been determined, the standard entropy change is easily calculated from the equation above.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the following table, the entropy terms are calculated from the experimental values of p*K*a and Δ*H*⊖.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The data were critically selected and refer to 25 °C and zero ionic strength, in water.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first point to note is that, when p*K*a is positive, the standard free energy change for the dissociation reaction is also positive.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Second, some reactions are exothermic and some are endothermic, but, when Δ*H*⊖ is negative *T*ΔS⊖ is the dominant factor, which determines that Δ*G*⊖ is positive.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Last, the entropy contribution is always unfavourable (Δ*S*⊖ < 0) in these reactions.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ions in aqueous solution tend to orient the surrounding water molecules, which orders the solution and decreases the entropy.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The contribution of an ion to the entropy is the partial molar entropy which is often negative, especially for small or highly charged ions.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The ionization of a neutral acid involves formation of two ions so that the entropy decreases (Δ*S*⊖ < 0).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the second ionization of the same acid, there are now three ions and the anion has a charge, so the entropy again decreases.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that the *standard* free energy change for the reaction is for the changes *from* the reactants in their standard states *to* the products in their standard states.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The free energy change *at* equilibrium is zero since the chemical potentials of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The experimental determination of p*K*a values is commonly performed by means of titrations, in a medium of high ionic strength and at constant temperature.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A solution of the compound in the medium is acidified with a strong acid to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The solution is then titrated with a strong base until all the protons have been removed.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constants are found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The total volume of added strong base should be small compared to the initial volume of titrand solution in order to keep the ionic strength nearly constant.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This will ensure that p*K*a remains invariant during the titration.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A calculated titration curve for oxalic acid is shown at the right.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Oxalic acid has p*K*a values of 1.27 and 4.27.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Therefore, the buffer regions will be centered at about pH 1.3 and pH 4.3.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The buffer regions carry the information necessary to get the p*K*a values as the concentrations of acid and conjugate base change along a buffer region.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Between the two buffer regions there is an end-point, or equivalence point, at about pH 3.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This end-point is not sharp and is typical of a diprotic acid whose buffer regions overlap by a small amount: p*K*a2 − p*K*a1 is about three in this example.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (If the difference in p*K* values were about two or less, the end-point would not be noticeable.) The second end-point begins at about pH 6.3 and is sharp.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This indicates that all the protons have been removed.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When this is so, the solution is not buffered and the pH rises steeply on addition of a small amount of strong base.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, the pH does not continue to rise indefinitely.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A new buffer region begins at about pH 11 (p*K*w − 3), which is where self-ionization of water becomes important.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is very difficult to measure pH values of less than two in aqueous solution with a glass electrode, because the Nernst equation breaks down at such low pH values.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To determine p*K* values of less than about 2 or more than about 11 spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be used instead of, or combined with, pH measurements.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the glass electrode cannot be employed, as with non-aqueous solutions, spectrophotometric methods are frequently used.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These may involve absorbance or fluorescence measurements.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In both cases the measured quantity is assumed to be proportional to the sum of contributions from each photo-active species; with absorbance measurements the Beer–Lambert law is assumed to apply.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) may be used to determine both a p*K* value and the corresponding standard enthalpy for acid dissociation.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Software to perform the calculations is supplied by the instrument manufacturers for simple systems.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Aqueous solutions with normal water cannot be used for 1H NMR measurements but heavy water, D2O, must be used instead.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] 13C NMR data, however, can be used with normal water and 1H NMR spectra can be used with non-aqueous media.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantities measured with NMR are time-averaged chemical shifts, as proton exchange is fast on the NMR time-scale.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other chemical shifts, such as those of 31P can be measured.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For some polyprotic acids, dissociation (or association) occurs at more than one nonequivalent site, and the observed macroscopic equilibrium constant, or macro-constant, is a combination of micro-constants involving distinct species.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When one reactant forms two products in parallel, the macro-constant is a sum of two micro-constants, $K=K_{X}+K_{Y}.$ This is true for example for the deprotonation of the amino acid cysteine, which exists in solution as a neutral zwitterion HS−CH2−CH(NH+3)−COO−.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Similarly, a base such as spermine has more than one site where protonation can occur.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, mono-protonation can occur at a terminal −NH2 group or at internal −NH− groups.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The *K*b values for dissociation of spermine protonated at one or other of the sites are examples of micro-constants.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They cannot be determined directly by means of pH, absorbance, fluorescence or NMR measurements; a measured *K*b value is the sum of the K values for the micro-reactions.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nevertheless, the site of protonation is very important for biological function, so mathematical methods have been developed for the determination of micro-constants.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a reactant undergoes two reactions in series, the macro-constant for the combined reaction is the product of the micro-constant for the two steps.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the quantitative treatment of systems involving acid–base equilibria in solution.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Many applications exist in biochemistry; for example, the p*K*a values of proteins and amino acid side chains are of major importance for the activity of enzymes and the stability of proteins.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Protein p*K*a values cannot always be measured directly, but may be calculated using theoretical methods.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions are used extensively to provide solutions at or near the physiological pH for the study of biochemical reactions; the design of these solutions depends on a knowledge of the p*K*a values of their components.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Important buffer solutions include MOPS, which provides a solution with pH 7.2, and tricine, which is used in gel electrophoresis.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffering is an essential part of acid base physiology including acid–base homeostasis, and is key to understanding disorders such as acid–base disorder.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The isoelectric point of a given molecule is a function of its p*K* values, so different molecules have different isoelectric points.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This permits a technique called isoelectric focusing, which is used for separation of proteins by 2-D gel polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions also play a key role in analytical chemistry.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] They are used whenever there is a need to fix the pH of a solution at a particular value.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Compared with an aqueous solution, the pH of a buffer solution is relatively insensitive to the addition of a small amount of strong acid or strong base.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The buffer capacity of a simple buffer solution is largest when pH = p*K*a.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In acid–base extraction, the efficiency of extraction of a compound into an organic phase, such as an ether, can be optimised by adjusting the pH of the aqueous phase using an appropriate buffer.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] At the optimum pH, the concentration of the electrically neutral species is maximised; such a species is more soluble in organic solvents having a low dielectric constant than it is in water.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This technique is used for the purification of weak acids and bases.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A pH indicator is a weak acid or weak base that changes colour in the transition pH range, which is approximately p*K*a ± 1.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The design of a universal indicator requires a mixture of indicators whose adjacent p*K*a values differ by about two, so that their transition pH ranges just overlap.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In pharmacology, ionization of a compound alters its physical behaviour and macro properties such as solubility and lipophilicity, log *p*).
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, ionization of any compound will increase the solubility in water, but decrease the lipophilicity.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This is exploited in drug development to increase the concentration of a compound in the blood by adjusting the p*K*a of an ionizable group.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the understanding of coordination complexes, which are formed by the interaction of a metal ion, Mm+, acting as a Lewis acid, with a ligand, L, acting as a Lewis base.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] To determine the equilibrium constant for this reaction, in which the ligand loses a proton, the p*K*a of the protonated ligand must be known.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In practice, the ligand may be polyprotic; for example EDTA4− can accept four protons; in that case, all p*K*a values must be known.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In addition, the metal ion is subject to hydrolysis, that is, it behaves as a weak acid, so the p*K* values for the hydrolysis reactions must also be known.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Assessing the hazard associated with an acid or base may require a knowledge of p*K*a values.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, hydrogen cyanide is a very toxic gas, because the cyanide ion inhibits the iron-containing enzyme cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Hydrogen cyanide is a weak acid in aqueous solution with a p*K*a of about 9.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In strongly alkaline solutions, above pH 11, say, it follows that sodium cyanide is "fully dissociated" so the hazard due to the hydrogen cyanide gas is much reduced.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] An acidic solution, on the other hand, is very hazardous because all the cyanide is in its acid form.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Ingestion of cyanide by mouth is potentially fatal, independently of pH, because of the reaction with cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In environmental science acid–base equilibria are important for lakes and rivers; for example, humic acids are important components of natural waters.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] There are multiple techniques to determine the p*K*a of a chemical, leading to some discrepancies between different sources.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Well measured values are typically within 0.1 units of each other.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Data presented here were taken at 25 °C in water.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] More values can be found in the Thermodynamics section, above.
[src:alginic-acid/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A table of p*K*a of carbon acids, measured in DMSO, can be found on the page on carbanions.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:alginic-acid/agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] It is a significant component of the biofilms produced by the bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, a major pathogen found in the lungs of some people who have cystic fibrosis.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] The biofilm and *P. aeruginosa* have a high resistance to antibiotics, but are susceptible to inhibition by macrophages.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginate was discovered by the British chemical scientist E.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Stanford in 1881, and he patented an extraction process for it in the same year.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] The alginate was extracted, in the original patent, by first soaking the algae in water or diluted acid.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] The resulting insoluble alginic acid is then treated with an alkaline solution such as sodium carbonate, creating sodium alginate, before finally precipitating and purifying the alginate from solution.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginic acid is a linear copolymer with homopolymeric blocks of (1→4)-linked β-D-mannuronate (M) and α-L-guluronate (G) residues, respectively, covalently linked together in different sequences or blocks.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] The monomers may appear in homopolymeric blocks of consecutive G-residues (G-blocks), consecutive M-residues (M-blocks) or alternating M and G-residues (MG-blocks). α-L-guluronate is the C-5 epimer of β-D-mannuronate.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginates are refined from brown seaweeds.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Throughout the world, many of the Phaeophyceae class brown seaweeds are harvested to be processed and converted into sodium alginate.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Sodium alginate is used in many industries including food, animal food, fertilisers, textile printing, and pharmaceuticals.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Dental impression material uses alginate as its means of gelling.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Food grade alginate is an approved ingredient in processed and manufactured foods.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Brown seaweeds range in size from the giant kelp *Macrocystis pyrifera* which can be 20–40 meters long, to thick, leather-like seaweeds from 2–4 m long, to smaller species 30–60 cm long.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Most brown seaweed used for alginates are gathered from the wild, with the exception of *Laminaria japonica*, which is cultivated in China for food and its surplus material is diverted to the alginate industry in China.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginates from different species of brown seaweed vary in their chemical structure, resulting in different physical properties of alginates.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Some species yield an alginate that gives a strong gel, another a weaker gel, some may produce a cream or white alginate, while others are difficult to gel and are best used for technical applications where color does not matter.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Commercial grade alginate is extracted from giant kelp *Macrocystis pyrifera*, *Ascophyllum nodosum*, and types of *Laminaria*.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginates are also produced by two bacterial genera *Pseudomonas* and *Azotobacter*, which played a major role in the unravelling of its biosynthesis pathway.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Bacterial alginates are useful for the production of micro- or nanostructures suitable for medical applications.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Sodium alginate (NaC6H7O6) is the sodium salt of alginic acid.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Potassium alginate (KC6H7O6) is the potassium salt of alginic acid.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Calcium alginate (CaC12H14O12) is the calcium salt of alginic acid.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] It is made by replacing the sodium ion in sodium alginate with a calcium ion (ion exchange).
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Chemically the process is simple, but difficulties arise from the physical separations required between the slimy residues from viscous solutions and the separation of gelatinous precipitates that hold large amounts of liquid within their structure, so they resist filtration and centrifugation.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] The conventional process involves large amounts of reagents and solvents, as well as time-consuming steps.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Simpler and newer techniques, such as microwave-assisted extraction, ultrasound, high pressure, pressurized fluid extraction, and enzyme-assisted extraction, are the subject of research.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] The most common, conventional extraction process involves six steps: pre-treatment of the algal biomass, acid treatment, alkaline extraction, precipitation, bleaching, and drying.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Pre-treatments mainly aim at either breaking the cell wall to help extract the alginate, or removing other compounds and contaminants from the algae.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Drying is of the first kind, also helping to prevent bacterial growth; algae which is dried is also usually powdered to expose more surface area.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Common treatments to remove contaminants include treatments with ethanol and formaldehyde, the latter of which is very common; ethanol solutions help remove compounds bonded to the alginate, and formaldehyde solutions help prevent enzymatic or microbial reactions.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] The algae is then treated with an acidic solution to help disrupt cell walls, which converts the alginate salts into insoluble alginic acid; a subsequently applied alkaline solution (pH 9-10), usually sodium carbonate, converts it back into water-soluble sodium alginate, which is then precipitated.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] It is also possible to extract the alginate directly with an alkaline treatment, but this is less common.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginic acid is usually precipitated, through different techniques, with either an alcohol (usually ethanol), calcium chloride, or hydrochloric acid.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] After the alginin is precipitated into a fine paste, it is dried, ground to the desired grain size, and finally purified through a variety of techniques.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Commercial alginate for biomedical and pharmaceutical use is extracted and purified through more rigorous techniques, but these are trade secrets.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Various alginate-based materials can be produced, including porous scaffold material, alginate hydrogel, nonwoven fabric, and alginate membranes.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Techniques used to produce these include ion cross-linking, microfluidic spinning, freeze drying, wet spinning, and immersive centrifugal jet spinning.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Calcium salts added to a sodium alginate solution to induce ionic cross-linking, which produces the hydrogel.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Freeze-drying the hydrogel to eliminate water produces the porous scaffold material.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Wet spinning consists of extruding an alginate solution from a spinneret into a calcium salt solution to induce ionic cross-linking (forming the gel), and then drawing the fibers out of the bath with draft rollers.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Microfluidic spinning, a simpler and more eco-friendly implementation of the process, involves introducing calcium salt flows flowing alongside and touching a central "core" flow of alginate.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] The fiber then emerges from the core flow.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] This technique can be used to produce shaped and grooved fibers.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginate fiber, which is used in fabric, is usually produced through either microfluidic spinning, wet spinning, or electrospinning to obtain thinner fibers.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Those fibers are used to produce alginate nonwoven fabric by carding and needle punching.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] The resulting felts are used in wound dressings, facial masks, and tissue scaffolds due to its hygroscopic and water retention ability.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] As of 2022, alginate had become one of the most preferred materials as an abundant natural biopolymer.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] It is particularly useful as a biomaterial because of its nontoxicity, hygroscopicity, and biocompatibility, and can imitate local bioenvironments; its degradation product can be easily cleared by the kidneys.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginate absorbs water quickly, which makes it useful as an additive in dehydrated products such as slimming aids, and in the manufacture of paper and textiles.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginate is also used for waterproofing and fireproofing fabrics, in the food industry as a thickening agent for drinks, ice cream, cosmetics, as a gelling agent for jellies, known by the code E401 and sausage casing.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Sodium alginate is mixed with soybean protein to make meat analogue.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginate is used as an ingredient in various pharmaceutical preparations, such as Gaviscon, in which it combines with bicarbonate to inhibit gastroesophageal reflux.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Sodium alginate is used as an impression-making material in dentistry, prosthetics, lifecasting, and for creating positives for small-scale casting.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Sodium alginate is used in reactive dye printing and as a thickener for reactive dyes in textile screen-printing.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginates do not react with these dyes and wash out easily, unlike starch-based thickeners.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] It also serves as a material for micro-encapsulation.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Calcium alginate is used in different types of medical products, including skin wound dressings, in the form of hydrogels, to promote healing, since alginate can increase the fluid uptake capacity of dressings, reducing the amount of times the dressing needs to be changed.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] In research on bone reconstruction, alginate composites have favorable properties encouraging regeneration, such as improved porosity, cell proliferation, and mechanical strength.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginate hydrogel is a common biomaterial for bio-fabrication of scaffolds and tissue regeneration.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Covalent bonding of thiol groups to alginate improves in-situ gelling and mucoadhesive properties; the thiolated polymer (thiomer) forms disulfide bonds within its polymeric network and with cysteine-rich subdomains of the mucus layer.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Thiolated alginates are used as in situ gelling hydrogels, and are under preliminary research as possible mucoadhesive drug delivery systems.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginate hydrogels may be used for drug delivery, exhibiting responses to pH changes, temperature changes, redox, and the presence of enzymes.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginate is one of the most widely used polymers in bioencapsulation, particularly for the immobilisation or protection of living cells, enzymes, proteins and other bioactive materials.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Its use is largely based on the ability of soluble alginate to form calcium alginate hydrogels under mild aqueous conditions, allowing biological material to be entrapped without exposure to harsh solvents, high temperature or aggressive chemical reactions.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] In cell encapsulation, alginate beads or microcapsules can provide a semipermeable hydrogel matrix that permits diffusion of nutrients, oxygen and secreted products while physically separating the encapsulated cells from the surrounding environment.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] This approach has been investigated for immunoisolation, islet transplantation, cell therapy, tissue engineering and controlled delivery of biological products.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] Alginate bioencapsulation systems can be produced by dripping, extrusion, air-jet cutting, electrostatic droplet generation, emulsification and microfluidic methods.
[src:alginic-acid/alginic-acid] These techniques differ in throughput, bead-size control, size distribution and suitability for encapsulating cells or labile biomolecules.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The **Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical** (**ATC**) **Classification System** is a drug classification system that classifies the active ingredients of drugs according to the organ or system on which they act and their therapeutic, pharmacological and chemical properties.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Its purpose is an aid to monitor drug use and for research to improve quality medication use.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] It does not imply drug recommendation or efficacy.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] It is controlled by the World Health Organization Collaborating Centre for Drug Statistics Methodology (WHOCC), and was first published in 1976.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] This pharmaceutical coding system divides drugs into different groups according to the organ or system on which they act, their therapeutic intent or nature, and the drug's chemical characteristics.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Different brands share the same code if they have the same active substance and indications.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Each bottom-level ATC code stands for a pharmaceutically used substance, or a combination of substances, in a single indication (or use).
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The ATC classification system is a strict hierarchy, meaning that each code necessarily has one and only one parent code, except for the 14 codes at the topmost level which have no parents.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The codes are semantic identifiers, meaning they depict information by themselves beyond serving as identifiers (namely, the codes depict themselves the complete lineage of parenthood).
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] As of 7 May 2020, there are 6,331 codes in ATC; the table below gives the count per level.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The ATC system is based on the earlier Anatomical Classification System, which is intended as a tool for the pharmaceutical industry to classify pharmaceutical products (as opposed to their active ingredients).
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] This system, confusingly also called ATC, was initiated in 1971 by the European Pharmaceutical Market Research Association (EphMRA) and is being maintained by the EphMRA and Intellus.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Its codes are organised into four levels.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The WHO's system, having five levels, is an extension and modification of the EphMRA's.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The first level of the code indicates the anatomical main group and consists of one letter.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The second level of the code indicates the therapeutic subgroup and consists of two digits.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The third level of the code indicates the therapeutic/pharmacological subgroup and consists of one letter.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The fourth level of the code indicates the chemical/therapeutic/pharmacological subgroup and consists of one letter.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The fifth level of the code indicates the chemical substance and consists of two digits.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The *Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical Classification System for veterinary medicinal products* (ATCvet) is used to classify veterinary drugs.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] ATCvet codes can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the ATC code of most human medications.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] For example, furosemide for veterinary use has the code **Q**C03CA01.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Some codes are used exclusively for veterinary drugs, such as *QI Immunologicals*, *QJ51 Antibacterials for intramammary use* or *QN05AX90 amperozide*.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The Herbal ATC system (HATC) is an ATC classification of herbal substances; it differs from the regular ATC system by using 4 digits instead of 2 at the 5th level group.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The herbal classification is not adopted by WHO.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The Uppsala Monitoring Centre is responsible for the Herbal ATC classification, and it is part of the WHODrug Global portfolio available by subscription.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The ATC system also includes defined daily doses (DDDs) for many drugs.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] This is a measurement of drug consumption based on the usual daily dose for a given drug.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] National issues of the ATC classification, such as the German *Anatomisch-therapeutisch-chemische Klassifikation mit Tagesdosen*, may include additional codes and DDDs not present in the WHO version.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] ATC follows guidelines in creating new codes for newly approved drugs.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] An application is submitted to WHO for ATC classification and DDD assignment.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] A preliminary or temporary code is assigned and published on the website and in the *WHO Drug Information* for comment or objection.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] New ATC/DDD codes are discussed at the semi-annual Working Group meeting.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] If accepted it becomes a final decision and published semi-annually on the website and *WHO Drug Information* and implemented in the annual print/on-line ACT/DDD Index on January 1.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Changes to existing ATC/DDD follow a similar process to become temporary codes and if accepted become a final decision as ATC/DDD alterations.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] ATC and DDD alterations are only valid and implemented in the coming annual updates; the original codes must continue until the end of the year.
[src:alginic-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] An updated version of the complete on-line/print ATC index with DDDs is published annually on January 1.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] An **antibiotic** is a type of antimicrobial substance which is active against bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] It is the most important type of antibacterial agent for fighting bacterial infections, and antibiotic medications are widely used in the treatment and prevention of such infections.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] They may either kill or inhibit the growth of bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] A limited number of antibiotics also possess antiprotozoal activity.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics are not effective against viruses such as the ones which cause the common cold or influenza.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Drugs which inhibit growth of viruses are termed antiviral drugs or antivirals.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics are also not effective against fungi.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Drugs which inhibit growth of fungi are called antifungal drugs.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] However, both classes have the same effect of killing or preventing the growth of microorganisms, and both are included in antimicrobial chemotherapy.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] "Antibacterials" include bactericides, bacteriostatics, antibacterial soaps, and chemical disinfectants, whereas antibiotics are an important class of antibacterials used more specifically in medicine and sometimes in livestock feed.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The earliest use of antibiotics was found in northern Sudan, where ancient Sudanese societies as early as 350–550 CE were systematically consuming antibiotics as part of their diet.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Chemical analyses of Nubian skeletons show consistent, high levels of tetracycline, a powerful antibiotic.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Researchers believe they were brewing beverages from grain fermented with *Streptomyces*, a bacterium that naturally produces tetracycline.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] This intentional routine use of antibiotics marks a foundational moment in medical history.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In other ancient civilizations, including Egypt, China, Serbia, Greece, and Rome, later evidence shows topical application of moldy bread to treat infections.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The first person to directly document the use of molds to treat infections was John Parkinson (1567–1650).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics revolutionized medicine in the 20th century.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Synthetic antibiotic chemotherapy as a science and the development of antibacterials began in Germany with Paul Ehrlich in the late 1880s.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Alexander Fleming (1881–1955) discovered modern-day penicillin in 1928, the widespread use of which proved significantly beneficial during wartime.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The first sulfonamide and the first systemically active antibacterial drug, Prontosil, was developed by a research team led by Gerhard Domagk in 1932 or 1933 at the Bayer Laboratories of the IG Farben conglomerate in Germany.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] However, the effectiveness and easy access to antibiotics have also led to their overuse and some bacteria have evolved resistance to them.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR), a naturally occurring process, is primarily driven by the misuse and overuse of antimicrobials.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Yet, at the same time, many people around the world do not have access to essential antimicrobials.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The World Health Organization has classified AMR as a widespread "serious threat [that] is no longer a prediction for the future, it is happening right now in every region of the world and has the potential to affect anyone, of any age, in any country".
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Each year, nearly 5 million deaths are associated with AMR globally.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Global deaths attributable to AMR numbered 1.27 million in 2019.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The term 'antibiosis', meaning "against life", was introduced by the French bacteriologist Jean Paul Vuillemin as a descriptive name of the phenomenon exhibited by these early antibacterial drugs.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiosis was first described in 1877 in bacteria when Louis Pasteur and Robert Koch observed that an airborne bacillus could inhibit the growth of *Bacillus anthracis*.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] These drugs were later renamed antibiotics by Selman Waksman, an American microbiologist, in 1947.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The term *antibiotic* was first used in 1942 by Selman Waksman and his collaborators in journal articles to describe any substance produced by a microorganism that is antagonistic to the growth of other microorganisms in high dilution.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] This definition excluded substances that kill bacteria but that are not produced by microorganisms (such as gastric juices and hydrogen peroxide).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] It also excluded synthetic antibacterial compounds such as the sulfonamides.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In current usage, the term "antibiotic" is applied to any medication that kills bacteria or inhibits their growth, regardless of whether that medication is produced by a microorganism or not.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The term "antibiotic" derives from *anti* + βιωτικός (*biōtikos*), "fit for life, lively", which comes from βίωσις (*biōsis*), "way of life", and that from βίος (*bios*), "life".
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The term "antibacterial" derives from Greek ἀντί (*anti*), "against" + βακτήριον (*baktērion*), diminutive of βακτηρία (*baktēria*), "staff, cane", because the first bacteria to be discovered were rod-shaped.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat or prevent bacterial infections, and sometimes protozoan infections.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] (Metronidazole is effective against a number of parasitic diseases).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] When an infection is suspected of being responsible for an illness but the responsible pathogen has not been identified, an empiric therapy is adopted.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] This involves the administration of a broad-spectrum antibiotic based on the signs and symptoms presented and is initiated pending laboratory results that can take several days.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] When the responsible pathogenic microorganism is already known or has been identified, definitive therapy can be started.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] This will usually involve the use of a narrow-spectrum antibiotic.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The choice of antibiotic given will also be based on its cost.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Identification is critically important as it can reduce the cost and toxicity of the antibiotic therapy and also reduce the possibility of the emergence of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] To avoid surgery, antibiotics may be given for non-complicated acute appendicitis.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics may be given as a preventive measure and this is usually limited to at-risk populations such as those with a weakened immune system (particularly in HIV cases to prevent pneumonia), those taking immunosuppressive drugs, cancer patients, and those having surgery.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Their use in surgical procedures is to help prevent infection of incisions.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] They have an important role in dental antibiotic prophylaxis where their use may prevent bacteremia and consequent infective endocarditis.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics are also used to prevent infection in cases of neutropenia particularly cancer-related.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The use of antibiotics for secondary prevention of coronary heart disease is not supported by current scientific evidence, and may actually increase cardiovascular mortality, all-cause mortality and the occurrence of stroke.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] There are many different routes of administration for antibiotic treatment.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In more severe cases, particularly deep-seated systemic infections, antibiotics can be given intravenously or by injection.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Where the site of infection is easily accessed, antibiotics may be given topically in the form of eye drops onto the conjunctiva for conjunctivitis or ear drops for ear infections and acute cases of swimmer's ear.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Topical use is also one of the treatment options for some skin conditions including acne and cellulitis.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Advantages of topical application include achieving high and sustained concentration of antibiotic at the site of infection; reducing the potential for systemic absorption and toxicity, and total volumes of antibiotic required are reduced, thereby also reducing the risk of antibiotic misuse.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Topical antibiotics applied over certain types of surgical wounds have been reported to reduce the risk of surgical site infections.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] However, there are certain general causes for concern with topical administration of antibiotics.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Some systemic absorption of the antibiotic may occur; the quantity of antibiotic applied is difficult to accurately dose, and there is also the possibility of local hypersensitivity reactions or contact dermatitis occurring.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] It is recommended to administer antibiotics as soon as possible, especially in life-threatening infections.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Many emergency departments stock antibiotics for this purpose.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotic consumption varies widely between countries.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The WHO report on surveillance of antibiotic consumption published in 2018 analysed 2015 data from 65 countries.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] As measured in defined daily doses per 1,000 inhabitants per day.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Mongolia had the highest consumption with a rate of 64.4.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Amoxicillin and amoxicillin/clavulanic acid were the most frequently consumed.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics are screened for any negative effects before their approval for clinical use, and are usually considered safe and well tolerated.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] However, some antibiotics have been associated with a wide extent of adverse side effects ranging from mild to very severe depending on the type of antibiotic used, the microbes targeted, and the individual patient.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Side effects may reflect the pharmacological or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or may involve hypersensitivity or allergic reactions.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Adverse effects range from fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Common side effects of oral antibiotics include diarrhea, resulting from disruption of the species composition in the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as *Clostridioides difficile*.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Taking probiotics during the course of antibiotic treatment can help prevent antibiotic-associated diarrhea.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibacterials can also affect the vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus *Candida* in the vulvo-vaginal area.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Additional side effects can result from interaction with other drugs, such as the possibility of tendon damage from the administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Some antibiotics may also damage the mitochondrion, a bacteria-derived organelle found in eukaryotic, including human, cells.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Mitochondrial damage causes oxidative stress in cells and has been suggested as a mechanism for side effects from fluoroquinolones.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics can also damage the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] It is also known to affect chloroplasts.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] There are few well-controlled studies on whether antibiotic use increases the risk of oral contraceptive failure.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The majority of studies indicate antibiotics do not interfere with birth control pills, such as clinical studies that suggest the failure rate of contraceptive pills caused by antibiotics is very low (about 1%).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Situations that may increase the risk of oral contraceptive failure include non-compliance (missing taking the pill), vomiting, or diarrhea.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Gastrointestinal disorders or interpatient variability in oral contraceptive absorption affecting ethinylestradiol serum levels in the blood.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Women with menstrual irregularities may be at higher risk of failure and should be advised to use backup contraception during antibiotic treatment and for one week after its completion.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] If patient-specific risk factors for reduced oral contraceptive efficacy are suspected, backup contraception is recommended.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In cases where antibiotics have been suggested to affect the efficiency of birth control pills, such as for the broad-spectrum antibiotic rifampicin, these cases may be due to an increase in the activities of hepatic liver enzymes' causing increased breakdown of the pill's active ingredients.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Effects on the intestinal flora, which might result in reduced absorption of estrogens in the colon, have also been suggested, but such suggestions have been inconclusive and controversial.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Clinicians have recommended that extra contraceptive measures be applied during therapies using antibiotics that are suspected to interact with oral contraceptives.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] More studies on the possible interactions between antibiotics and birth control pills (oral contraceptives) are required as well as careful assessment of patient-specific risk factors for potential oral contractive pill failure prior to dismissing the need for backup contraception.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Interactions between alcohol and certain antibiotics may occur and may cause side effects and decreased effectiveness of antibiotic therapy.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] While moderate alcohol consumption is unlikely to interfere with many common antibiotics, there are specific types of antibiotics with which alcohol consumption may cause serious side effects.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Therefore, potential risks of side effects and effectiveness depend on the type of antibiotic administered.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics such as metronidazole, tinidazole, cephamandole, latamoxef, cefoperazone, cefmenoxime, and furazolidone, cause a disulfiram-like chemical reaction with alcohol by inhibiting its breakdown by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, which may result in vomiting, nausea, and shortness of breath.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In addition, the efficacy of doxycycline and erythromycin succinate may be reduced by alcohol consumption.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Other effects of alcohol on antibiotic activity include altered activity of the liver enzymes that break down the antibiotic compound.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The successful outcome of antimicrobial therapy with antibacterial compounds depends on several factors.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] These include host defense mechanisms, the location of infection, and the pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic properties of the antibacterial.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The bactericidal activity of antibacterials may depend on the bacterial growth phase, and it often requires ongoing metabolic activity and division of bacterial cells.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] These findings are based on laboratory studies, and in clinical settings have also been shown to eliminate bacterial infection.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Since the activity of antibacterials depends frequently on its concentration, *in vitro* characterization of antibacterial activity commonly includes the determination of the minimum inhibitory concentration and minimum bactericidal concentration of an antibacterial.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] To predict clinical outcome, the antimicrobial activity of an antibacterial is usually combined with its pharmacokinetic profile, and several pharmacological parameters are used as markers of drug efficacy.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In important infectious diseases, including tuberculosis, combination therapy (i.e., the concurrent application of two or more antibiotics) has been used to delay or prevent the emergence of resistance.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In acute bacterial infections, antibiotics as part of combination therapy are prescribed for their synergistic effects to improve treatment outcome as the combined effect of both antibiotics is better than their individual effect.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Fosfomycin has the highest number of synergistic combinations among antibiotics and is almost always used as a partner drug.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Combination therapy also broadens the antimicrobial spectrum, ensuring that at least one of the antibiotics in the regimen is effective against the pathogen, which is especially important when the causative agent is unknown.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* infections may be treated with a combination therapy of fusidic acid and rifampicin.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics used in combination may also be antagonistic and the combined effects of the two antibiotics may be less than if one of the antibiotics was given as a monotherapy.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] For example, chloramphenicol and tetracyclines are antagonists to penicillins.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] However, this can vary depending on the species of bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In general, combinations of a bacteriostatic antibiotic and bactericidal antibiotic are antagonistic.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In addition to combining one antibiotic with another, antibiotics are sometimes co-administered with resistance-modifying agents.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] For example, β-lactam antibiotics may be used in combination with β-lactamase inhibitors, such as clavulanic acid or sulbactam, when a patient is infected with a β-lactamase-producing strain of bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics are commonly classified based on their mechanism of action, chemical structure, or spectrum of activity.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Most target bacterial functions or growth processes.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Those that target the bacterial cell wall (penicillins and cephalosporins) or the cell membrane (polymyxins), or interfere with essential bacterial enzymes (rifamycins, lipiarmycins, quinolones, and sulfonamides) have bactericidal activities, killing the bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Protein synthesis inhibitors (macrolides, lincosamides, and tetracyclines) are usually bacteriostatic, inhibiting further growth (with the exception of bactericidal aminoglycosides).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Further categorization is based on their target specificity.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] "Narrow-spectrum" antibiotics target specific types of bacteria, such as gram-negative or gram-positive, whereas broad-spectrum antibiotics affect a wide range of bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] With advances in medicinal chemistry, most modern antibacterials are semisynthetic modifications of various natural compounds.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] These include, for example, the beta-lactam antibiotics, which include the penicillins (produced by fungi in the genus *Penicillium*), the cephalosporins, and the carbapenems.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Compounds that are still isolated from living organisms are the aminoglycosides, whereas other antibacterials—for example, the sulfonamides, the quinolones, and the oxazolidinones—are produced solely by chemical synthesis.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Many antibacterial compounds are relatively small molecules with a molecular weight of less than 1000 daltons.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Since the first pioneering efforts of Howard Florey and Chain in 1939, the importance of antibiotics, including antibacterials, to medicine has led to intense research into producing antibacterials at large scales.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Following screening of antibacterials against a wide range of bacteria, production of the active compounds is carried out using fermentation, usually in strongly aerobic conditions.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR or AR) is a naturally occurring process.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] AMR is driven largely by the misuse and overuse of antimicrobials.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria is a common phenomenon mainly caused by the overuse/misuse.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] It represents a threat to health globally.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Emergence of resistance often reflects evolutionary processes that take place during antibiotic therapy.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The antibiotic treatment may select for bacterial strains with physiologically or genetically enhanced capacity to survive high doses of antibiotics.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Under certain conditions, it may result in preferential growth of resistant bacteria, while growth of susceptible bacteria is inhibited by the drug.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] For example, antibacterial selection for strains having previously acquired antibacterial-resistance genes was demonstrated in 1943 by the Luria–Delbrück experiment.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics such as penicillin and erythromycin, which used to have a high efficacy against many bacterial species and strains, have become less effective, due to the increased resistance of many bacterial strains.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Resistance may take the form of biodegradation of pharmaceuticals, such as sulfamethazine-degrading soil bacteria introduced to sulfamethazine through medicated pig feces.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The survival of bacteria often results from an inheritable resistance, but the growth of resistance to antibacterials also occurs through horizontal gene transfer.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Horizontal transfer is more likely to happen in locations of frequent antibiotic use.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibacterial resistance may impose a biological cost, thereby reducing fitness of resistant strains, which can limit the spread of antibacterial-resistant bacteria, for example, in the absence of antibacterial compounds.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Additional mutations, however, may compensate for this fitness cost and can aid the survival of these bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Paleontological data show that both antibiotics and antibiotic resistance are ancient compounds and mechanisms.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Useful antibiotic targets are those for which mutations negatively impact bacterial reproduction or viability.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Several molecular mechanisms of antibacterial resistance exist.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Intrinsic antibacterial resistance may be part of the genetic makeup of bacterial strains.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] For example, an antibiotic target may be absent from the bacterial genome.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Acquired resistance results from a mutation in the bacterial chromosome or the acquisition of extra-chromosomal DNA.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibacterial-producing bacteria have evolved resistance mechanisms that have been shown to be similar to, and may have been transferred to, antibacterial-resistant strains.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The spread of antibacterial resistance often occurs through vertical transmission of mutations during growth and by genetic recombination of DNA by horizontal genetic exchange.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] For instance, antibacterial resistance genes can be exchanged between different bacterial strains or species via plasmids that carry these resistance genes.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Plasmids that carry several different resistance genes can confer resistance to multiple antibacterials.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Cross-resistance to several antibacterials may also occur when a resistance mechanism encoded by a single gene conveys resistance to more than one antibacterial compound.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibacterial-resistant strains and species, sometimes referred to as "superbugs", now contribute to the emergence of diseases that were, for a while, well controlled.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] For example, emergent bacterial strains causing tuberculosis that are resistant to previously effective antibacterial treatments pose many therapeutic challenges.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Every year, nearly half a million new cases of multidrug-resistant tuberculosis (MDR-TB) are estimated to occur worldwide.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] For example, NDM-1 is a newly identified enzyme conveying bacterial resistance to a broad range of beta-lactam antibacterials.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In recent years, even anaerobic bacteria, historically considered less concerning in terms of resistance, have demonstrated high rates of antibiotic resistance, particularly *Bacteroides*, for which resistance rates to penicillin have been reported to exceed 90%.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Per *The ICU Book*, "The first rule of antibiotics is to try not to use them, and the second rule is try not to use too many of them." Inappropriate antibiotic treatment and overuse of antibiotics have contributed to the emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] However, potential harm from antibiotics extends beyond selection of antimicrobial resistance and their overuse is associated with adverse effects for patients themselves, seen most clearly in critically ill patients in Intensive care units.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Self-prescribing of antibiotics is an example of misuse.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Many antibiotics are frequently prescribed to treat symptoms or diseases that do not respond to antibiotics or that are likely to resolve without treatment.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Also, incorrect or suboptimal antibiotics are prescribed for certain bacterial infections.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The overuse of antibiotics, like penicillin and erythromycin, has been associated with emerging antibiotic resistance since the 1950s.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Widespread usage of antibiotics in hospitals has also been associated with increases in bacterial strains and species that no longer respond to treatment with the most common antibiotics.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Common forms of antibiotic misuse include excessive use of prophylactic antibiotics in travelers and failure of medical professionals to prescribe the correct dosage of antibiotics on the basis of the patient's weight and history of prior use.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Other forms of misuse include failure to take the entire prescribed course of the antibiotic, incorrect dosage and administration, or failure to rest for sufficient recovery.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Inappropriate antibiotic treatment, for example, is their prescription to treat viral infections such as the common cold.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] One study on respiratory tract infections found "physicians were more likely to prescribe antibiotics to patients who appeared to expect them".
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Multifactorial interventions aimed at both physicians and patients can reduce inappropriate prescription of antibiotics.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The lack of rapid point of care diagnostic tests, particularly in resource-limited settings is considered one of the drivers of antibiotic misuse.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Several organizations concerned with antimicrobial resistance are lobbying to eliminate the unnecessary use of antibiotics.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The issues of misuse and overuse of antibiotics have been addressed by the formation of the US Interagency Task Force on Antimicrobial Resistance.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] This task force aims to actively address antimicrobial resistance, and is coordinated by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), and the National Institutes of Health, as well as other US agencies.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] A non-governmental organization campaign group is *Keep Antibiotics Working*.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In France, an "Antibiotics are not automatic" government campaign started in 2002 and led to a marked reduction of unnecessary antibiotic prescriptions, especially in children.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The emergence of antibiotic resistance has prompted restrictions on their use in the UK in 1970 (Swann report 1969), and the European Union has banned the use of antibiotics as growth-promotional agents since 2003.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Moreover, several organizations (including the World Health Organization, the National Academy of Sciences, and the U.S.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Food and Drug Administration) have advocated restricting the amount of antibiotic use in food animal production.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] 2562) aimed at phasing out nontherapeutic use of antibiotics in US food animals were proposed, but have not passed.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] These bills were endorsed by public health and medical organizations, including the American Holistic Nurses' Association, the American Medical Association, and the American Public Health Association.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Despite pledges by food companies and restaurants to reduce or eliminate meat that comes from animals treated with antibiotics, the purchase of antibiotics for use on farm animals has been increasing every year.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] There has been extensive use of antibiotics in animal husbandry.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In the United States, the question of emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains due to use of antibiotics in livestock was raised by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in 1977.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In March 2012, the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York, ruling in an action brought by the Natural Resources Defense Council and others, ordered the FDA to revoke approvals for the use of antibiotics in livestock, which violated FDA regulations.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Studies have shown that common misconceptions about the effectiveness and necessity of antibiotics to treat common mild illnesses contribute to their overuse.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Other forms of antibiotic-associated harm include anaphylaxis, drug toxicity most notably kidney and liver damage, and super-infections with resistant organisms.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Antibiotics are also known to affect mitochondrial function, and this may contribute to the bioenergetic failure of immune cells seen in sepsis.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] They also alter the microbiome of the gut, lungs, and skin, which may be associated with adverse effects such as Clostridioides difficile associated diarrhoea.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Whilst antibiotics can clearly be lifesaving in patients with bacterial infections, their overuse, especially in patients where infections are hard to diagnose, can lead to harm via multiple mechanisms.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Before the early 20th century, treatments for infections were based primarily on medicinal folklore.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Mixtures with antimicrobial properties used in the treatment of infections were described over 2,000 years ago.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Many ancient cultures, including the ancient Egyptians and ancient Greeks, used specially selected mold and plant materials to treat infections.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Nubian mummies studied in the 1990s were found to contain significant levels of tetracycline.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The beer brewed at that time was conjectured to have been the source.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The use of antibiotics in modern medicine began with the discovery of synthetic antibiotics derived from dyes.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Various essential oils have been shown to have anti-microbial properties.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Along with this, the plants from which these oils have been derived can be used as niche anti-microbial agents.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Ehrlich noted certain dyes would colour human, animal, or bacterial cells, whereas others did not.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] He then proposed that it might be possible to create chemicals that would act as a selective drug that would bind to and kill bacteria without harming the human host.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] After screening hundreds of dyes against various organisms, in 1907, he discovered a medicinally useful drug, the first synthetic antibacterial organoarsenic compound salvarsan, now called arsphenamine.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] This heralded the era of antibacterial treatment that was begun with the discovery of a series of arsenic-derived synthetic antibiotics by both Alfred Bertheim and Ehrlich in 1907.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Ehrlich and Bertheim had experimented with various chemicals derived from dyes to treat trypanosomiasis in mice and spirochaeta infection in rabbits.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] While their early compounds were too toxic, Ehrlich and Sahachiro Hata, a Japanese bacteriologist working with Ehrlich in the quest for a drug to treat syphilis, achieved success with the 606th compound in their series of experiments.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In 1910, Ehrlich and Hata announced their discovery, which they called drug "606", at the Congress for Internal Medicine at Wiesbaden.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The Hoechst company began to market the compound toward the end of 1910 under the name Salvarsan, now known as arsphenamine.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The drug was used to treat syphilis in the first half of the 20th century.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In 1908, Ehrlich received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his contributions to immunology.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Hata was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1911 and for the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1912 and 1913.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The first sulfonamide and the first systemically active antibacterial drug, Prontosil, was developed by a research team led by Gerhard Domagk in 1932 or 1933 at the Bayer Laboratories of the IG Farben conglomerate in Germany, for which Domagk received the 1939 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Sulfanilamide, the active drug of Prontosil, was not patentable as it had already been in use in the dye industry for some years.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Prontosil had a relatively broad effect against Gram-positive cocci, but not against enterobacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Research was stimulated apace by its success.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The discovery and development of this sulfonamide drug opened the era of antibacterials.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Observations about the growth of some microorganisms inhibiting the growth of other microorganisms have been reported since the late 19th century.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] These observations of antibiosis between microorganisms led to the discovery of natural antibacterials.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Louis Pasteur observed, "if we could intervene in the antagonism observed between some bacteria, it would offer perhaps the greatest hopes for therapeutics".
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In 1874, physician Sir William Roberts noted that cultures of the mould *Penicillium glaucum* that is used in the making of some types of blue cheese did not display bacterial contamination.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In 1895, Vincenzo Tiberio, an Italian physician, published a paper on the antibacterial power of some extracts of mold.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In his thesis, Duchesne proposed that bacteria and moulds engage in a perpetual battle for survival.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Duchesne observed that *E. coli* was eliminated by *Penicillium glaucum* when grown in the same culture.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] He also observed that when he inoculated laboratory animals with lethal doses of typhoid bacilli together with *Penicillium glaucum*, the animals did not contract typhoid.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Duchesne's army service after getting his degree prevented him from doing any further research.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Duchesne died of tuberculosis, a disease now treated by antibiotics.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In 1928, Sir Alexander Fleming postulated the existence of penicillin, a molecule produced by certain moulds that kills or stops the growth of certain kinds of bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Fleming was working on a culture of disease-causing bacteria when he noticed the spores of a green mold, *Penicillium rubens*, in one of his culture plates.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] He observed that the presence of the mould killed or prevented the growth of the bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Fleming postulated that the mould must secrete an antibacterial substance, which he named penicillin in 1928.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Fleming believed that its antibacterial properties could be exploited for chemotherapy.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] He initially characterised some of its biological properties and attempted to use a crude preparation to treat some infections, but he was unable to pursue its further development without the aid of trained chemists.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Ernst Chain, Howard Florey, and Edward Abraham succeeded in purifying the first penicillin, penicillin G, in 1942, but it did not become widely available outside the Allied military before 1945.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Later, Norman Heatley developed the back extraction technique for efficiently purifying penicillin in bulk.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] The chemical structure of penicillin was first proposed by Abraham in 1942 and then later confirmed by Dorothy Crowfoot Hodgkin in 1945.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Purified penicillin displayed potent antibacterial activity against a wide range of bacteria and had low toxicity in humans.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Furthermore, its activity was not inhibited by biological constituents such as pus, unlike the synthetic sulfonamides.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] (see below) The development of penicillin led to renewed interest in the search for antibiotic compounds with similar efficacy and safety.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] For their successful development of penicillin, which Fleming had accidentally discovered but could not develop himself, as a therapeutic drug, Chain and Florey shared the 1945 Nobel Prize in Medicine with Fleming.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Florey credited René Dubos with pioneering the approach of deliberately and systematically searching for antibacterial compounds, which had led to the discovery of gramicidin and had revived Florey's research in penicillin.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] In 1939, coinciding with the start of World War II, Dubos had reported the discovery of the first naturally derived antibiotic, tyrothricin, a compound of 20% gramicidin and 80% tyrocidine, from *Bacillus brevis*.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] It was one of the first commercially manufactured antibiotics and was very effective in treating wounds and ulcers during World War II.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Gramicidin, however, could not be used systemically because of toxicity.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Tyrocidine also proved too toxic for systemic usage.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] Research results obtained during that period were not shared between the Axis and the Allied powers during World War II and limited access during the Cold War.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] During the mid-20th century, the number of new antibiotic substances introduced for medical use increased significantly.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] From 1935 to 1968, 12 new classes were launched.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p01] However, the number of new classes dropped markedly, with only two new classes introduced between 1969 and 2003.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Both the WHO and the Infectious Disease Society of America report that the weak antibiotic pipeline does not match bacteria's increasing ability to develop resistance.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The Infectious Disease Society of America report noted that the number of new antibiotics approved for marketing per year had been declining and identified seven antibiotics against the Gram-negative bacilli currently in phase 2 or phase 3 clinical trials.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] However, these drugs did not address the entire spectrum of resistance of Gram-negative bacilli.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] According to the WHO fifty one new therapeutic entities - antibiotics (including combinations), are in phase 1–3 clinical trials as of May 2017.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Antibiotics targeting multidrug-resistant Gram-positive pathogens remains a high priority.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] A few antibiotics have received marketing authorization in the last seven years.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The cephalosporin ceftaroline and the lipoglycopeptides oritavancin and telavancin have been approved for the treatment of acute bacterial skin and skin structure infection and community-acquired bacterial pneumonia.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The lipoglycopeptide dalbavancin and the oxazolidinone tedizolid has also been approved for use for the treatment of acute bacterial skin and skin structure infection.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The first in a new class of narrow-spectrum macrocyclic antibiotics, fidaxomicin, has been approved for the treatment of *C. difficile* colitis.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] New cephalosporin-lactamase inhibitor combinations also approved include ceftazidime-avibactam and ceftolozane-avibactam for complicated urinary tract infection and intra-abdominal infection.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Possible improvements include clarification of clinical trial regulations by FDA.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Furthermore, appropriate economic incentives could persuade pharmaceutical companies to invest in this endeavor.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] In the US, the Antibiotic Development to Advance Patient Treatment (ADAPT) Act was introduced with the aim of fast tracking the drug development of antibiotics to combat the growing threat of 'superbugs'.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Under this Act, FDA can approve antibiotics and antifungals treating life-threatening infections based on smaller clinical trials.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The CDC will monitor the use of antibiotics and the emerging resistance, and publish the data.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The FDA antibiotics labeling process, 'Susceptibility Test Interpretive Criteria for Microbial Organisms' or 'breakpoints', will provide accurate data to healthcare professionals.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Because antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains continue to emerge and spread, there is a constant need to develop new antibacterial treatments.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Bacteria, fungi, plants, animals and other organisms are being screened in the search for new antibiotics.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Most of the antibiotics in current use are natural products or natural product derivatives, and bacterial, fungal, plant and animal extracts are being screened in the search for new antibiotics.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Organisms may be selected for testing based on ecological, ethnomedical, genomic, or historical rationales.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Medicinal plants, for example, are screened on the basis that they are used by traditional healers to prevent or cure infection and may therefore contain antibacterial compounds.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Also, soil bacteria are screened on the basis that, historically, they have been a very rich source of antibiotics (with 70 to 80% of antibiotics in current use derived from the actinomycetes).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] In addition to screening natural products for direct antibacterial activity, they are sometimes screened for the ability to suppress antibiotic resistance and antibiotic tolerance.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] For example, some secondary metabolites inhibit drug efflux pumps, thereby increasing the concentration of antibiotic able to reach its cellular target and decreasing bacterial resistance to the antibiotic.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Natural products known to inhibit bacterial efflux pumps include the alkaloid lysergol, the carotenoids capsanthin and capsorubin, and the flavonoids rotenone and chrysin.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Other natural products, this time primary metabolites rather than secondary metabolites, have been shown to eradicate antibiotic tolerance.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] For example, glucose, mannitol, and fructose reduce antibiotic tolerance in *Escherichia coli* and *Staphylococcus aureus*, rendering them more susceptible to killing by aminoglycoside antibiotics.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Natural products may be screened for the ability to suppress bacterial virulence factors too.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Examples of natural products with antivirulence activity include the flavonoid epigallocatechin gallate (which inhibits listeriolysin O), the quinone tetrangomycin (which inhibits staphyloxanthin), and the sesquiterpene zerumbone (which inhibits *Acinetobacter baumannii* motility).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Antibodies (anti-tetanus immunoglobulin) have been used in the treatment and prevention of tetanus since the 1910s, and this approach continues to be a useful way of controlling bacterial diseases.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The monoclonal antibody bezlotoxumab, for example, has been approved by the US FDA and EMA for recurrent Clostridioides difficile infection, and other monoclonal antibodies are in development (e.g.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] AR-301 for the adjunctive treatment of *S. aureus* ventilator-associated pneumonia).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Antibody treatments act by binding to and neutralizing bacterial exotoxins and other virulence factors.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Phage therapy is under investigation as a method of treating antibiotic-resistant strains of bacteria.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Phage therapy involves infecting bacterial pathogens with viruses.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Bacteriophages and their host ranges are extremely specific for certain bacteria, thus, unlike antibiotics, they do not disturb the host organism's intestinal microbiota.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Bacteriophages, also known as phages, infect and kill bacteria primarily during lytic cycles.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Phages insert their DNA into the bacterium, where it is transcribed and used to make new phages, after which the cell will lyse, releasing new phage that are able to infect and destroy further bacteria of the same strain.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The high specificity of phage protects "good" bacteria from destruction.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Some disadvantages to the use of bacteriophages also exist, however.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Bacteriophages may harbour virulence factors or toxic genes in their genomes and, prior to use, it may be prudent to identify genes with similarity to known virulence factors or toxins by genomic sequencing.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] In addition, the oral and IV administration of phages for the eradication of bacterial infections poses a much higher safety risk than topical application.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Also, there is the additional concern of uncertain immune responses to these large antigenic cocktails.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] There are considerable regulatory hurdles that must be cleared for such therapies.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Despite numerous challenges, the use of bacteriophages as a replacement for antimicrobial agents against MDR pathogens that no longer respond to conventional antibiotics, remains an attractive option.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Fecal microbiota transplants involve transferring the full intestinal microbiota from a healthy human donor (in the form of stool) to patients with *C. difficile* infection.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Although this procedure has not been officially approved by the US FDA, its use is permitted under some conditions in patients with antibiotic-resistant *C. difficile* infection.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Cure rates are around 90%, and work is underway to develop stool banks, standardized products, and methods of oral delivery.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Fecal microbiota transplantation has also been used more recently for inflammatory bowel diseases.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The antisense RNA then hybridizes with the bacterial mRNA and blocks its translation into the essential protein.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Antisense RNA-based treatment has been shown to be effective in *in vivo* models of *P. aeruginosa* pneumonia.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] In addition to silencing essential bacterial genes, antisense RNA can be used to silence bacterial genes responsible for antibiotic resistance.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] For example, antisense RNA has been developed that silences the *S. aureus* *mecA* gene (the gene that encodes modified penicillin-binding protein 2a and renders *S. aureus* strains methicillin-resistant).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Antisense RNA targeting *mecA* mRNA has been shown to restore the susceptibility of methicillin-resistant staphylococci to oxacillin in both *in vitro* and *in vivo* studies.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] In the early 2000s, a system was discovered that enables bacteria to defend themselves against invading viruses.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The system, known as CRISPR-Cas9, consists of (a) an enzyme that destroys DNA (the nuclease Cas9) and (b) the DNA sequences of previously encountered viral invaders (CRISPR).
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] These viral DNA sequences enable the nuclease to target foreign (viral) rather than self (bacterial) DNA.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Although the function of CRISPR-Cas9 in nature is to protect bacteria, the DNA sequences in the CRISPR component of the system can be modified so that the Cas9 nuclease targets bacterial resistance genes or bacterial virulence genes instead of viral genes.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] The modified CRISPR-Cas9 system can then be administered to bacterial pathogens using plasmids or bacteriophages.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] This approach has successfully been used to silence antibiotic resistance and reduce the virulence of enterohemorrhagic *E. coli* in an *in vivo* model of infection.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] In addition to developing new antibacterial treatments, it is important to reduce the selection pressure for the emergence and spread of antimicrobial resistance (AMR), such as antibiotic resistance.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Antibiotic cycling, where antibiotics are alternated by clinicians to treat microbial diseases, is proposed, but recent studies revealed such strategies are ineffective against antibiotic resistance.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Vaccines are an essential part of the response to reduce AMR as they prevent infections, reduce the use and overuse of antimicrobials, and slow the emergence and spread of drug-resistant pathogens.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Vaccination either excites or reinforces the immune competence of a host to ward off infection, leading to the activation of macrophages, the production of antibodies, inflammation, and other classic immune reactions.
[src:alginic-acid/antibiotics-p02] Antibacterial vaccines have been responsible for a drastic reduction in global bacterial diseases.
[src:alginic-acid/arbaclofen-placarbil] It is being developed as an addiction medicine to treat alcoholism.
[src:alginic-acid/arbaclofen-placarbil] It is also studied as a potential therapy for some autistic subjects.
[src:alginic-acid/atc-code-a02] Codes for veterinary use (ATCvet codes) can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the human ATC code: for example, **QA02**.
[src:alginic-acid/atc-code-a02] National versions of the ATC classification may include additional codes not present in this list, which follows the WHO version.
